Name: Color-shade
Description: A slight degree of difference between colors, especially with regard to how light or dark it is or as distinguished from one nearly like it.

Name: Dark-shade
Description: A color tone not reflecting much light.

Name: Light-shade
Description: A color tone reflecting more light.

Name: Grayscale
Description: Using a color map composed of shades of gray, varying from black at the weakest intensity to white at the strongest.

Name: HSV-color
Description: A color representation that models how colors appear under light.

Name: Hue
Description: Attribute of a visual sensation according to which an area appears to be similar to one of the perceived colors.

Name: Saturation
Description: Colorfulness of a stimulus relative to its own brightness.

Name: HSV-value
Description: An attribute of a visual sensation according to which an area appears to emit more or less light.

Name: RGB-color
Description: A color from the RGB schema.

Name: RGB-red
Description: The red component.

Name: RGB-blue
Description: The blue component.

Name: RGB-green
Description: The green component.

Name: Luminance
Description: A quality that exists by virtue of the luminous intensity per unit area projected in a given direction.

Name: Opacity
Description: A measure of impenetrability to light.

Name: Sensory-presentation
Description: The entity has a sensory manifestation.

Name: Auditory-presentation
Description: The sense of hearing is used in the presentation to the user.

Name: Loudspeaker-separation
Description: The distance between two loudspeakers. Grouped with the Distance tag.

Name: Monophonic
Description: Relating to sound transmission, recording, or reproduction involving a single transmission path.

Name: Silent
Description: The absence of ambient audible sound or the state of having ceased to produce sounds.

Name: Stereophonic
Description: Relating to, or constituting sound reproduction involving the use of separated microphones and two transmission channels to achieve the sound separation of a live hearing.

Name: Gustatory-presentation
Description: The sense of taste used in the presentation to the user.

Name: Olfactory-presentation
Description: The sense of smell used in the presentation to the user.

Name: Somatic-presentation
Description: The nervous system is used in the presentation to the user.

Name: Tactile-presentation
Description: The sense of touch used in the presentation to the user.

Name: Vestibular-presentation
Description: The sense balance used in the presentation to the user.

Name: Visual-presentation
Description: The sense of sight used in the presentation to the user.

Name: 2D-view
Description: A view showing only two dimensions.

Name: 3D-view
Description: A view showing three dimensions.

Name: Background-view
Description: Parts of the view that are farthest from the viewer and usually the not part of the visual focus.

Name: Bistable-view
Description: Something having two stable visual forms that have two distinguishable stable forms as in optical illusions.

Name: Foreground-view
Description: Parts of the view that are closest to the viewer and usually the most important part of the visual focus.

Name: Foveal-view
Description: Visual presentation directly on the fovea. A view projected on the small depression in the retina containing only cones and where vision is most acute.

Name: Map-view
Description: A diagrammatic representation of an area of land or sea showing physical features, cities, roads.

Name: Aerial-view
Description: Elevated view of an object from above, with a perspective as though the observer were a bird.

Name: Satellite-view
Description: A representation as captured by technology such as a satellite.

Name: Street-view
Description: A 360-degrees panoramic view from a position on the ground.

Name: Peripheral-view
Description: Indirect vision as it occurs outside the point of fixation.

Name: Task-property
Description: Something that pertains to a task.

Name: Task-attentional-demand
Description: Strategy for allocating attention toward goal-relevant information.

Name: Bottom-up-attention
Description: Attentional guidance purely by externally driven factors to stimuli that are salient because of their inherent properties relative to the background. Sometimes this is referred to as stimulus driven.

Name: Covert-attention
Description: Paying attention without moving the eyes.

Name: Divided-attention
Description: Integrating parallel multiple stimuli. Behavior involving responding simultaneously to multiple tasks or multiple task demands.

Name: Focused-attention
Description: Responding discretely to specific visual, auditory, or tactile stimuli.

Name: Orienting-attention
Description: Directing attention to a target stimulus.

Name: Overt-attention
Description: Selectively processing one location over others by moving the eyes to point at that location.

Name: Selective-attention
Description: Maintaining a behavioral or cognitive set in the face of distracting or competing stimuli. Ability to pay attention to a limited array of all available sensory information.

Name: Sustained-attention
Description: Maintaining a consistent behavioral response during continuous and repetitive activity.

Name: Switched-attention
Description: Having to switch attention between two or more modalities of presentation.

Name: Top-down-attention
Description: Voluntary allocation of attention to certain features. Sometimes this is referred to goal-oriented attention.

Name: Task-effect-evidence
Description: The evidence supporting the conclusion that the event had the specified effect.

Name: Computational-evidence
Description: A type of evidence in which data are produced, and/or generated, and/or analyzed on a computer.

Name: External-evidence
Description: A phenomenon that follows and is caused by some previous phenomenon.

Name: Intended-effect
Description: A phenomenon that is intended to follow and be caused by some previous phenomenon.

Name: Behavioral-evidence
Description: An indication or conclusion based on the behavior of an agent.

Name: Task-event-role
Description: The purpose of an event with respect to the task.

Name: Experimental-stimulus
Description: Part of something designed to elicit a response in the experiment.

Name: Incidental
Description: A sensory or other type of event that is unrelated to the task or experiment.

Name: Instructional
Description: Usually associated with a sensory event intended to give instructions to the participant about the task or behavior.

Name: Mishap
Description: Unplanned disruption such as an equipment or experiment control abnormality or experimenter error.

Name: Participant-response
Description: Something related to a participant actions in performing the task.

Name: Task-activity
Description: Something that is part of the overall task or is necessary to the overall experiment but is not directly part of a stimulus-response cycle. Examples would be taking a survey or provided providing a silva sample.

Name: Warning
Description: Something that should warn the participant that the parameters of the task have been or are about to be exceeded such as a warning message about getting too close to the shoulder of the road in a driving task.

Name: Task-action-type
Description: How an agent action should be interpreted in terms of the task specification.

Name: Appropriate-action
Description: An action suitable or proper in the circumstances.

Name: Correct-action
Description: An action that was a correct response in the context of the task.

Name: Correction
Description: An action offering an improvement to replace a mistake or error.

Name: Done-indication
Description: An action that indicates that the participant has completed this step in the task.

Name: Incorrect-action
Description: An action considered wrong or incorrect in the context of the task.

Name: Imagined-action
Description: Form a mental image or concept of something. This is used to identity something that only happened in the imagination of the participant as in imagined movements in motor imagery paradigms.

Name: Inappropriate-action
Description: An action not in keeping with what is correct or proper for the task.

Name: Indeterminate-action
Description: An action that cannot be distinguished between two or more possibibities in the current context. This tag might be applied when an outside evaluator or a classification algorithm cannot determine a definitive result.

Name: Omitted-action
Description: An expected response was skipped.

Name: Miss
Description: An action considered to be a failure in the context of the task. For example, if the agent is supposed to try to hit a target and misses.

Name: Near-miss
Description: An action barely satisfied the requirements of the task. In a driving experiment for example this could pertain to a narrowly avoided collision or other accident.

Name: Ready-indication
Description: An action that indicates that the participant is ready to perform the next step in the task.

Name: Task-relationship
Description: Specifying organizational importance of sub-tasks.

Name: Background-subtask
Description: A part of the task which should be performed in the background as for example inhibiting blinks due to instruction while performing the primary task.

Name: Primary-subtask
Description: A part of the task which should be the primary focus of the participant.

Name: Task-stimulus-role
Description: The role the stimulus plays in the task.

Name: Cue
Description: A signal for an action, a pattern of stimuli indicating a particular response.

Name: Distractor
Description: A person or thing that distracts or a plausible but incorrect option in a multiple-choice question. In pyschological studies this is sometimes referred to as a foil.

Name: Expected
Description: Considered likely, probable or anticipated. Something of low information value as in frequent non-targets in an RSVP paradigm.

Name: Extraneous
Description: Irrelevant or unrelated to the subject being dealt with.

Name: Feedback
Description: An evaluative response to an inquiry, process, event, or activity.

Name: Go-signal
Description: An indicator to proceed with a planned action.

Name: Meaningful
Description: Conveying significant or relevant information.

Name: Newly-learned
Description: Representing recently acquired information or understanding.

Name: Non-informative
Description: Something that is not useful in forming an opinion or judging an outcome.

Name: Non-target
Description: Something other than that done or looked for. Also tag Expected if the Non-target is frequent.

Name: Not-meaningful
Description: Not having a serious, important, or useful quality or purpose.

Name: Novel
Description: Having no previous example or precedent or parallel.

Name: Oddball
Description: Something unusual, or infrequent.

Name: Planned
Description: Something that was decided on or arranged in advance.

Name: Penalty
Description: A disadvantage, loss, or hardship due to some action.

Name: Priming
Description: An implicit memory effect in which exposure to a stimulus influences response to a later stimulus.

Name: Query
Description: A sentence of inquiry that asks for a reply.

Name: Reward
Description: A positive reinforcement for a desired action, behavior or response.

Name: Stop-signal
Description: An indicator that the agent should stop the current activity.

Name: Target
Description: Something fixed as a goal, destination, or point of examination.

Name: Threat
Description: An indicator that signifies hostility and predicts an increased probability of attack.

Name: Timed
Description: Something planned or scheduled to be done at a particular time or lasting for a specified amount of time.

Name: Unexpected
Description: Something that is not anticipated.

Name: Unplanned
Description: Something that has not been planned as part of the task.

Name: Relation
Description: Concerns the way in which two or more people or things are connected.

Name: Comparative-relation
Description: Something considered in comparison to something else. The first argument is the focus.

Name: Approximately-equal-to
Description: (A, (Approximately-equal-to, B)) indicates that A and B have almost the same value. Here A and B could refer to sizes, orders, positions or other quantities.

Name: Less-than
Description: (A, (Less-than, B)) indicates that A is smaller than B. Here A and B could refer to sizes, orders, positions or other quantities.

Name: Less-than-or-equal-to
Description: (A, (Less-than-or-equal-to, B)) indicates that the relative size or order of A is smaller than or equal to B.

Name: Greater-than
Description: (A, (Greater-than, B)) indicates that the relative size or order of A is bigger than that of B.

Name: Greater-than-or-equal-to
Description: (A, (Greater-than-or-equal-to, B)) indicates that the relative size or order of A is bigger than or the same as that of B.

Name: Equal-to
Description: (A, (Equal-to, B)) indicates that the size or order of A is the same as that of B.

Name: Not-equal-to
Description: (A, (Not-equal-to, B)) indicates that the size or order of A is not the same as that of B.

Name: Connective-relation
Description: Indicates two items are related in some way.

Name: Belongs-to
Description: (A, (Belongs-to, B)) indicates that A is a member of B.

Name: Connected-to
Description: (A, (Connected-to, B)) indicates that A is related to B in some respect, usually through a direct link.

Name: Contained-in
Description: (A, (Contained-in, B)) indicates that A is completely inside of B.

Name: Described-by
Description: (A, (Described-by, B)) indicates that B provides information about A.

Name: From-to
Description: (A, (From-to, B)) indicates a directional relation from A to B. A is considered the source.

Name: Group-of
Description: (A, (Group-of, B)) indicates A is a group of items of type B.

Name: Implied-by
Description: (A, (Implied-by, B)) indicates B is suggested by A.

Name: Includes
Description: (A, (Includes, B)) indicates that A has B as a member or part.

Name: Interacts-with
Description: (A, (Interacts-with, B)) indicates A and B interact, possibly reciprocally.

Name: Member-of
Description: (A, (Member-of, B)) indicates A is a member of group B.

Name: Part-of
Description: (A, (Part-of, B)) indicates A is a part of the whole B.

Name: Performed-by
Description: (A, (Performed-by, B)) indicates that the action or procedure A was carried out by agent B.

Name: Performed-using
Description: A, (Performed-using, B)) indicates that the action or procedure A was accomplished using B.

Name: Related-to
Description: (A, (Related-to, B)) indicates A has some relationship to B.

Name: Unrelated-to
Description: (A, (Unrelated-to, B)) indicates that A is not related to B.  For example, A is not related to Task.

Name: Directional-relation
Description: A relationship indicating direction of change.

Name: Away-from
Description: (A, (Away-from, B)) indicates that A is going or has moved away from B. The meaning depends on A and B.

Name: Towards
Description: (A, (Towards, B)) indicates that A is going to or has moved to B. The meaning depends on A and B.

Name: Spatial-relation
Description: Indicating information about position.

Name: Above
Description: (A, (Above, B)) means A is in a place or position that is higher than B.

Name: Across-from
Description: (A, (Across-from, B)) means A is on the opposite side of something from B.

Name: Adjacent-to
Description: (A, (Adjacent-to, B)) indicates that A is next to B in time or space.

Name: Ahead-of
Description: (A, (Ahead-of, B)) indicates that A is further forward in time or space in B.

Name: Around
Description: (A, (Around, B)) means A is in or near the present place or situation of B.

Name: Behind
Description: (A, (Behind, B)) means A is at or to the far side of B, typically so as to be hidden by it.

Name: Below
Description: (A, (Below, B)) means A is in a place or position that is lower than the position of B.

Name: Between
Description: (A, (Between, (B, C))) means A is in the space or interval separating B and C.

Name: Bilateral-to
Description: (A, (Bilateral, B)) means A is on both sides of B or affects both sides of B.

Name: Bottom-edge-of
Description: (A, (Bottom-edge-of, B)) means A is on the bottom most part or or near the boundary of B.

Name: Boundary-of
Description: (A, (Boundary-of, B)) means A is on or part of the edge or boundary of B.

Name: Center-of
Description: (A, (Center-of, B)) means A is at a point or or in an area that is approximately central within B.

Name: Close-to
Description: (A, (Close-to, B)) means A is at a small distance from or is located near in space to B.

Name: Far-from
Description: (A, (Far-from, B)) means A is at a large distance from or is not located near in space to B.

Name: In-front-of
Description: (A, (In-front-of, B)) means A is in a position just ahead or at the front part of B, potentially partially blocking B from view.

Name: Left-edge-of
Description: (A, (Left-edge-of, B)) means A is located on the left side of B on or near the boundary of B.

Name: Left-side-of
Description: (A, (Left-side-of, B)) means A is located on the left side of B usually as part of B.

Name: Lower-left-of
Description: (A, (Lower-left-of, B)) means A is situated on the lower left part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Name: Lower-right-of
Description: (A, (Lower-right-of, B)) means A is situated on the lower right part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Name: Outside-of
Description: (A, (Outside-of, B)) means A is located in the space around but not including B.

Name: Over
Description: (A, (Over, B)) means A above is above B so as to cover or protect or A extends over the a general area as from a from a vantage point.

Name: Right-edge-of
Description: (A, (Right-edge-of, B)) means A is located on the right side of B on or near the boundary of B.

Name: Right-side-of
Description: (A, (Right-side-of, B)) means A is located on the right side of B usually as part of B.

Name: To-left-of
Description: (A, (To-left-of, B)) means A is located on or directed toward the side to the west of B when B is facing north. This term is used when A is not part of B.

Name: To-right-of
Description: (A, (To-right-of, B)) means A is located on or directed toward the side to the east of B when B is facing north. This term is used when A is not part of B.

Name: Top-edge-of
Description: (A, (Top-edge-of, B)) means A is on the uppermost part or or near the boundary of B.

Name: Top-of
Description: (A, (Top-of, B)) means A is on the uppermost part, side, or surface of B.

Name: Upper-left-of
Description: (A, (Upper-left-of, B)) means A is situated on the upper left part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Name: Upper-right-of
Description: (A, (Upper-right-of, B)) means A is situated on the upper right part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Name: Underneath
Description: (A, (Underneath, B)) means A is situated directly below and may be concealed by B.

Name: Within
Description: (A, (Within, B)) means A is on the inside of or contained in B.

Name: Temporal-relation
Description: Any relationship which includes a temporal or time-based component.

Name: After
Description: (A, (After B)) means A happens at a time subsequent to a reference time related to B.

Name: Asynchronous-with
Description: (A, (Asynchronous-with, B)) means A happens at times not occurring at the same time or having the same period or phase as B.

Name: Before
Description: (A, (Before B)) means A happens at a time earlier in time or order than B.

Name: During
Description: (A, (During, B)) means A happens at some point in a given period of time in which B is ongoing.

Name: Synchronous-with
Description: (A, (Synchronous-with, B)) means A happens at occurs at the same time or rate as B.

Name: Waiting-for
Description: (A, (Waiting-for, B)) means A pauses for something to happen in B.

Name: Modulator
Description: External stimuli / interventions or changes in the alertness level (sleep) that modify: the background activity, or how often a graphoelement is occurring, or change other features of the graphoelement (like intra-burst frequency). For each observed finding, there is an option of specifying how they are influenced by the modulators and procedures that were done during the recording.

Name: Sleep-modulator
Description: No description available

Name: Sleep-deprivation
Description: No description available

Name: Sleep-following-sleep-deprivation
Description: No description available

Name: Natural-sleep
Description: No description available

Name: Induced-sleep
Description: No description available

Name: Drowsiness
Description: No description available

Name: Awakening
Description: No description available

Name: Medication-modulator
Description: No description available

Name: Medication-administered-during-recording
Description: No description available

Name: Medication-withdrawal-or-reduction-during-recording
Description: No description available

Name: Eye-modulator
Description: No description available

Name: Manual-eye-closure
Description: No description available

Name: Manual-eye-opening
Description: No description available

Name: Stimulation-modulator
Description: No description available

Name: Intermittent-photic-stimulation
Description: No description available

Name: Auditory-stimulation
Description: No description available

Name: Nociceptive-stimulation
Description: No description available

Name: Hyperventilation
Description: No description available

Name: Physical-effort
Description: No description available

Name: Cognitive-task
Description: No description available

Name: Other-modulator-or-procedure
Description: No description available

Name: Background-activity
Description: An EEG activity representing the setting in which a given normal or abnormal pattern appears and from which such pattern is distinguished.

Name: Posterior-dominant-rhythm
Description: Rhythmic activity occurring during wakefulness over the posterior regions of the head, generally with maximum amplitudes over the occipital areas. Amplitude varies. Best seen with eyes closed and during physical relaxation and relative mental inactivity. Blocked or attenuated by attention, especially visual, and mental effort. In adults this is the alpha rhythm, and the frequency is 8 to 13 Hz. However the frequency can be higher or lower than this range (often a supra or sub harmonic of alpha frequency) and is called alpha variant rhythm (fast and slow alpha variant rhythm). In children, the normal range of the frequency of the posterior dominant rhythm is age-dependant.

Name: Mu-rhythm
Description: EEG rhythm at 7-11 Hz composed of arch-shaped waves occurring over the central or centro-parietal regions of the scalp during wakefulness. Amplitudes varies but is mostly below 50 microV. Blocked or attenuated most clearly by contralateral movement, thought of movement, readiness to move or tactile stimulation.

Name: Other-organized-rhythm
Description: EEG activity that consisting of waves of approximately constant period, which is considered as part of the background (ongoing) activity, but does not fulfill the criteria of the posterior dominant rhythm.

Name: Background-activity-special-feature
Description: Special Features. Special features contains scoring options for the background activity of critically ill patients.

Name: Continuous-background-activity
Description: No description available

Name: Nearly-continuous-background-activity
Description: No description available

Name: Discontinuous-background-activity
Description: No description available

Name: Background-burst-suppression
Description: EEG pattern consisting of bursts (activity appearing and disappearing abruptly) interrupted by periods of low amplitude (below 20 microV) and which occurs simultaneously over all head regions.

Name: Background-burst-attenuation
Description: No description available

Name: Background-activity-suppression
Description: Periods showing activity under 10 microV (referential montage) and interrupting the background (ongoing) activity.

Name: Electrocerebral-inactivity
Description: Absence of any ongoing cortical electric activities; in all leads EEG is isoelectric or only contains artifacts. Sensitivity has to be increased up to 2 microV/mm; recording time: at least 30 minutes.

Name: Sleep-and-drowsiness
Description: The features of the ongoing activity during sleep are scored here. If abnormal graphoelements appear, disappear or change their morphology during sleep, that is not scored here but at the entry corresponding to that graphooelement (as a modulator).

Name: Sleep-architecture
Description: For longer recordings. Only to be scored if whole-night sleep is part of the recording. It is a global descriptor of the structure and pattern of sleep: estimation of the amount of time spent in REM and NREM sleep, sleep duration, NREM-REM cycle.

Name: Normal-sleep-architecture
Description: No description available

Name: Abnormal-sleep-architecture
Description: No description available

Name: Sleep-stage-reached
Description: For normal sleep patterns the sleep stages reached during the recording can be specified

Name: Sleep-stage-N1
Description: Sleep stage 1.

Name: Sleep-stage-N2
Description: Sleep stage 2.

Name: Sleep-stage-N3
Description: Sleep stage 3.

Name: Sleep-stage-REM
Description: Rapid eye movement.

Name: Sleep-spindles
Description: Burst at 11-15 Hz but mostly at 12-14 Hz generally diffuse but of higher voltage over the central regions of the head, occurring during sleep. Amplitude varies but is mostly below 50 microV in the adult.

Name: Arousal-pattern
Description: Arousal pattern in children. Prolonged, marked high voltage 4-6/s activity in all leads with some intermixed slower frequencies, in children.

Name: Frontal-arousal-rhythm
Description: Prolonged (up to 20s) rhythmical sharp or spiky activity over the frontal areas (maximum over the frontal midline) seen at arousal from sleep in children with minimal cerebral dysfunction.

Name: Vertex-wave
Description: Sharp potential, maximal at the vertex, negative relative to other areas, apparently occurring spontaneously during sleep or in response to a sensory stimulus during sleep or wakefulness. May be single or repetitive. Amplitude varies but rarely exceeds 250 microV. Abbreviation: V wave. Synonym: vertex sharp wave.

Name: K-complex
Description: A burst of somewhat variable appearance, consisting most commonly of a high voltage negative slow wave followed by a smaller positive slow wave frequently associated with a sleep spindle. Duration greater than 0.5 s. Amplitude is generally maximal in the frontal vertex. K complexes occur during nonREM sleep, apparently spontaneously, or in response to sudden sensory / auditory stimuli, and are not specific for any individual sensory modality.

Name: Saw-tooth-waves
Description: Vertex negative 2-5 Hz waves occuring in series during REM sleep

Name: POSTS
Description: Positive occipital sharp transients of sleep. Sharp transient maximal over the occipital regions, positive relative to other areas, apparently occurring spontaneously during sleep. May be single or repetitive. Amplitude varies but is generally bellow 50 microV.

Name: Hypnagogic-hypersynchrony
Description: Bursts of bilateral, synchronous delta or theta activity of large amplitude, occasionally with superimposed faster components, occurring during falling asleep or during awakening, in children.

Name: Non-reactive-sleep
Description: EEG activity consisting of normal sleep graphoelements, but which cannot be interrupted by external stimuli/ the patient cannot be waken.

Name: Interictal-finding
Description: EEG pattern / transient that is distinguished form the background activity, considered abnormal, but is not recorded during ictal period (seizure) or postictal period; the presence of an interictal finding does not necessarily imply that the patient has epilepsy.

Name: Epileptiform-interictal-activity
Description: No description available

Name: Abnormal-interictal-rhythmic-activity
Description: No description available

Name: Interictal-special-patterns
Description: No description available

Name: Interictal-periodic-discharges
Description: Periodic discharge not further specified (PDs).

Name: Generalized-periodic-discharges
Description: GPDs.

Name: Lateralized-periodic-discharges
Description: LPDs.

Name: Bilateral-independent-periodic-discharges
Description: BIPDs.

Name: Multifocal-periodic-discharges
Description: MfPDs.

Name: Extreme-delta-brush
Description: No description available

Name: Critically-ill-patients-patterns
Description: Rhythmic or periodic patterns in critically ill patients (RPPs) are scored according to the 2012 version of the American Clinical Neurophysiology Society Standardized Critical Care EEG Terminology (Hirsch et al., 2013).

Name: Critically-ill-patients-periodic-discharges
Description: Periodic discharges (PDs).

Name: Rhythmic-delta-activity
Description: RDA

Name: Spike-or-sharp-and-wave
Description: SW

Name: Episode
Description: Clinical episode or electrographic seizure.

Name: Epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Focal-onset-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Aware-focal-onset-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Impaired-awareness-focal-onset-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Awareness-unknown-focal-onset-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Focal-to-bilateral-tonic-clonic-focal-onset-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Generalized-onset-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Unknown-onset-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Unclassified-epileptic-seizure
Description: No description available

Name: Subtle-seizure
Description: Seizure type frequent in neonates, sometimes referred to as motor automatisms; they may include random and roving eye movements, sucking, chewing motions, tongue protrusion, rowing or swimming or boxing movements of the arms, pedaling and bicycling movements of the lower limbs; apneic seizures are relatively common. Although some subtle seizures are associated with rhythmic ictal EEG discharges, and are clearly epileptic, ictal EEG often does not show typical epileptic activity.

Name: Electrographic-seizure
Description: Referred usually to non convulsive status. Ictal EEG: rhythmic discharge or spike and wave pattern with definite evolution in frequency, location, or morphology lasting at least 10 s; evolution in amplitude alone did not qualify.

Name: Seizure-PNES
Description: Psychogenic non-epileptic seizure.

Name: Sleep-related-episode
Description: No description available

Name: Sleep-related-arousal
Description: Normal.

Name: Benign-sleep-myoclonus
Description: A distinctive disorder of sleep characterized by a) neonatal onset, b) rhythmic myoclonic jerks only during sleep and c) abrupt and consistent cessation with arousal, d) absence of concomitant electrographic changes suggestive of seizures, and e) good outcome.

Name: Confusional-awakening
Description: Episode of non epileptic nature included in NREM parasomnias, characterized by sudden arousal and complex behavior but without full alertness, usually lasting a few minutes and occurring almost in all children at least occasionally. Amnesia of the episode is the rule.

Name: Sleep-periodic-limb-movement
Description: PLMS. Periodic limb movement in sleep. Episodes are characterized by brief (0.5- to 5.0-second) lower-extremity movements during sleep, which typically occur at 20- to 40-second intervals, most commonly during the first 3 hours of sleep. The affected individual is usually not aware of the movements or of the transient partial arousals.

Name: REM-sleep-behavioral-disorder
Description: REM sleep behavioral disorder. Episodes characterized by: a) presence of REM sleep without atonia (RSWA) on polysomnography (PSG); b) presence of at least 1 of the following conditions - (1) Sleep-related behaviors, by history, that have been injurious, potentially injurious, or disruptive (example: dream enactment behavior); (2) abnormal REM sleep behavior documented during PSG monitoring; (3) absence of epileptiform activity on electroencephalogram (EEG) during REM sleep (unless RBD can be clearly distinguished from any concurrent REM sleep-related seizure disorder); (4) sleep disorder not better explained by another sleep disorder, a medical or neurologic disorder, a mental disorder, medication use, or a substance use disorder.

Name: Sleep-walking
Description: Episodes characterized by ambulation during sleep; the patient is difficult to arouse during an episode, and is usually amnesic following the episode. Episodes usually occur in the first third of the night during slow wave sleep. Polysomnographic recordings demonstrate 2 abnormalities during the first sleep cycle: frequent, brief, non-behavioral EEG-defined arousals prior to the somnambulistic episode and abnormally low gamma (0.75-2.0 Hz) EEG power on spectral analysis, correlating with high-voltage (hyper-synchronic gamma) waves lasting 10 to 15 s occurring just prior to the movement. This is followed by stage I NREM sleep, and there is no evidence of complete awakening.

Name: Pediatric-episode
Description: No description available

Name: Hyperekplexia
Description: Disorder characterized by exaggerated startle response and hypertonicity that may occur during the first year of life and in severe cases during the neonatal period. Children usually present with marked irritability and recurrent startles in response to handling and sounds. Severely affected infants can have severe jerks and stiffening, sometimes with breath-holding spells.

Name: Jactatio-capitis-nocturna
Description: Relatively common in normal children at the time of going to bed, especially during the first year of life, the rhythmic head movements persist during sleep. Usually, these phenomena disappear before 3 years of age.

Name: Pavor-nocturnus
Description: A nocturnal episode characterized by age of onset of less than five years (mean age 18 months, with peak prevalence at five to seven years), appearance of signs of panic two hours after falling asleep with crying, screams, a fearful expression, inability to recognize other people including parents (for a duration of 5-15 minutes), amnesia upon awakening. Pavor nocturnus occurs in patients almost every night for months or years (but the frequency is highly variable and may be as low as once a month) and is likely to disappear spontaneously at the age of six to eight years.

Name: Pediatric-stereotypical-behavior-episode
Description: Repetitive motor behavior in children, typically rhythmic and persistent; usually not paroxysmal and rarely suggest epilepsy. They include headbanging, head-rolling, jactatio capitis nocturna, body rocking, buccal or lingual movements, hand flapping and related mannerisms, repetitive hand-waving (to self-induce photosensitive seizures).

Name: Paroxysmal-motor-event
Description: Paroxysmal phenomena during neonatal or childhood periods characterized by recurrent motor or behavioral signs or symptoms that must be distinguishes from epileptic disorders.

Name: Syncope
Description: Episode with loss of consciousness and muscle tone that is abrupt in onset, of short duration and followed by rapid recovery; it occurs in response to transient impairment of cerebral perfusion. Typical prodromal symptoms often herald onset of syncope and postictal symptoms are minimal. Syncopal convulsions resulting from cerebral anoxia are common but are not a form of epilepsy, nor are there any accompanying EEG ictal discharges.

Name: Cataplexy
Description: A sudden decrement in muscle tone and loss of deep tendon reflexes, leading to muscle weakness, paralysis, or postural collapse. Cataplexy usually is precipitated by an outburst of emotional expression-notably laughter, anger, or startle. It is one of the tetrad of symptoms of narcolepsy. During cataplexy, respiration and voluntary eye movements are not compromised. Consciousness is preserved.

Name: Other-episode
Description: No description available

Name: Physiologic-pattern
Description: EEG graphoelements or rhythms that are considered normal. They only should be scored if the physician considers that they have a specific clinical significance for the recording.

Name: Rhythmic-activity-pattern
Description: Not further specified.

Name: Slow-alpha-variant-rhythm
Description: Characteristic rhythms mostly at 4-5 Hz, recorded most prominently over the posterior regions of the head. Generally alternate, or are intermixed, with alpha rhythm to which they often are harmonically related. Amplitude varies but is frequently close to 50 micro V. Blocked or attenuated by attention, especially visual, and mental effort. Comment: slow alpha variant rhythms should be distinguished from posterior slow waves characteristic of children and adolescents and occasionally seen in young adults.

Name: Fast-alpha-variant-rhythm
Description: Characteristic rhythm at 14-20 Hz, detected most prominently over the posterior regions of the head. May alternate or be intermixed with alpha rhythm. Blocked or attenuated by attention, especially visual, and mental effort.

Name: Ciganek-rhythm
Description: Midline theta rhythm (Ciganek rhythm) may be observed during wakefulness or drowsiness. The frequency is 4-7 Hz, and the location is midline (ie, vertex). The morphology is rhythmic, smooth, sinusoidal, arciform, spiky, or mu-like.

Name: Lambda-wave
Description: Diphasic sharp transient occurring over occipital regions of the head of waking subjects during visual exploration. The main component is positive relative to other areas. Time-locked to saccadic eye movement. Amplitude varies but is generally below 50 micro V.

Name: Posterior-slow-waves-youth
Description: Waves in the delta and theta range, of variable form, lasting 0.35 to 0.5 s or longer without any consistent periodicity, found in the range of 6-12 years (occasionally seen in young adults). Alpha waves are almost always intermingled or superimposed. Reactive similar to alpha activity.

Name: Diffuse-slowing-hyperventilation
Description: Diffuse slowing induced by hyperventilation. Bilateral, diffuse slowing during hyperventilation. Recorded in 70 percent of normal children (3-5 years) and less then 10 percent of adults. Usually appear in the posterior regions and spread forward in younger age group, whereas they tend to appear in the frontal regions and spread backward in the older age group.

Name: Photic-driving
Description: Physiologic response consisting of rhythmic activity elicited over the posterior regions of the head by repetitive photic stimulation at frequencies of about 5-30 Hz. Comments: term should be limited to activity time-locked to the stimulus and of frequency identical or harmonically related to the stimulus frequency. Photic driving should be distinguished from the visual evoked potentials elicited by isolated flashes of light or flashes repeated at very low frequency.

Name: Photomyogenic-response
Description: A response to intermittent photic stimulation characterized by the appearance in the record of brief, repetitive muscular artifacts (spikes) over the anterior regions of the head. These often increase gradually in amplitude as stimuli are continued and cease promptly when the stimulus is withdrawn. Comment: this response is frequently associated with flutter of the eyelids and vertical oscillations of the eyeballs and sometimes with discrete jerking mostly involving the musculature of the face and head. (Preferred to synonym: photo-myoclonic response).

Name: Other-physiologic-pattern
Description: No description available

Name: Uncertain-significant-pattern
Description: EEG graphoelements or rhythms that resemble abnormal patterns but that are not necessarily associated with a pathology, and the physician does not consider them abnormal in the context of the scored recording (like normal variants and patterns).

Name: Sharp-transient-pattern
Description: No description available

Name: Wicket-spikes
Description: Spike-like monophasic negative single waves or trains of waves occurring over the temporal regions during drowsiness that have an arcuate or mu-like appearance. These are mainly seen in older individuals and represent a benign variant that is of little clinical significance.

Name: Small-sharp-spikes
Description: Benign epileptiform Transients of Sleep (BETS). Small sharp spikes (SSS) of very short duration and low amplitude, often followed by a small theta wave, occurring in the temporal regions during drowsiness and light sleep. They occur on one or both sides (often asynchronously). The main negative and positive components are of about equally spiky character. Rarely seen in children, they are seen most often in adults and the elderly. Two thirds of the patients have a history of epileptic seizures.

Name: Fourteen-six-Hz-positive-burst
Description: Burst of arch-shaped waves at 13-17 Hz and/or 5-7-Hz but most commonly at 14 and or 6 Hz seen generally over the posterior temporal and adjacent areas of one or both sides of the head during sleep. The sharp peaks of its component waves are positive with respect to other regions. Amplitude varies but is generally below 75  micro V. Comments: (1) best demonstrated by referential recording using contralateral earlobe or other remote, reference electrodes. (2) This pattern has no established clinical significance.

Name: Six-Hz-spike-slow-wave
Description: Spike and slow wave complexes at 4-7Hz, but mostly at 6 Hz occurring generally in brief bursts bilaterally and synchronously, symmetrically or asymmetrically, and either confined to or of larger amplitude over the posterior or anterior regions of the head. The spike has a strong positive component. Amplitude varies but is generally smaller than that of spike-and slow-wave complexes repeating at slower rates. Comment: this pattern should be distinguished from epileptiform discharges. Synonym: wave and spike phantom.

Name: Rudimentary-spike-wave-complex
Description: Synonym: Pseudo petit mal discharge. Paroxysmal discharge that consists of generalized or nearly generalized high voltage 3 to 4/sec waves with poorly developed spike in the positive trough between the slow waves, occurring in drowsiness only. It is found only in infancy and early childhood when marked hypnagogic rhythmical theta activity is paramount in the drowsy state.

Name: Slow-fused-transient
Description: A posterior slow-wave preceded by a sharp-contoured potential that blends together with the ensuing slow wave, in children.

Name: Needle-like-occipital-spikes-blind
Description: Spike discharges of a particularly fast and needle-like character develop over the occipital region in most congenitally blind children. Completely disappear during childhood or adolescence.

Name: Subclinical-rhythmic-EEG-discharge-adults
Description: Subclinical rhythmic EEG discharge of adults (SERDA). A rhythmic pattern seen in the adult age group, mainly in the waking state or drowsiness. It consists of a mixture of frequencies, often predominant in the theta range. The onset may be fairly abrupt with widespread sharp rhythmical theta and occasionally with delta activity. As to the spatial distribution, a maximum of this discharge is usually found over the centroparietal region and especially over the vertex. It may resemble a seizure discharge but is not accompanied by any clinical signs or symptoms.

Name: Rhythmic-temporal-theta-burst-drowsiness
Description: Rhythmic temporal theta burst of drowsiness (RTTD). Characteristic burst of 4-7 Hz waves frequently notched by faster waves, occurring over the temporal regions of the head during drowsiness. Synonym: psychomotor variant pattern. Comment: this is a pattern of drowsiness that is of no clinical significance.

Name: Temporal-slowing-elderly
Description: Focal theta and/or delta activity over the temporal regions, especially the left, in persons over the age of 60. Amplitudes are low/similar to the background activity. Comment: focal temporal theta was found in 20 percent of people between the ages of 40-59 years, and 40 percent of people between 60 and 79 years. One third of people older than 60 years had focal temporal delta activity.

Name: Breach-rhythm
Description: Rhythmical activity recorded over cranial bone defects. Usually it is in the 6 to 11/sec range, does not respond to movements.

Name: Other-uncertain-significant-pattern
Description: No description available

Name: Artifact
Description: When relevant for the clinical interpretation, artifacts can be scored by specifying the type and the location.

Name: Biological-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Eye-blink-artifact
Description: Example for EEG: Fp1/Fp2 become electropositive with eye closure because the cornea is positively charged causing a negative deflection in Fp1/Fp2. If the eye blink is unilateral, consider prosthetic eye. If it is in F8 rather than Fp2 then the electrodes are plugged in wrong.

Name: Eye-movement-horizontal-artifact
Description: Example for EEG: There is an upward deflection in the Fp2-F8 derivation, when the eyes move to the right side. In this case F8 becomes more positive and therefore. When the eyes move to the left, F7 becomes more positive and there is an upward deflection in the Fp1-F7 derivation.

Name: Eye-movement-vertical-artifact
Description: Example for EEG: The EEG shows positive potentials (50-100 micro V) with bi-frontal distribution, maximum at Fp1 and Fp2, when the eyeball rotated upward. The downward rotation of the eyeball was associated with the negative deflection. The time course of the deflections was similar to the time course of the eyeball movement.

Name: Slow-eye-movement-artifact
Description: Slow, rolling eye-movements, seen during drowsiness.

Name: Nystagmus-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Chewing-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Sucking-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Glossokinetic-artifact
Description: The tongue functions as a dipole, with the tip negative with respect to the base. The artifact produced by the tongue has a broad potential field that drops from frontal to occipital areas, although it is less steep than that produced by eye movement artifacts. The amplitude of the potentials is greater inferiorly than in parasagittal regions; the frequency is variable but usually in the delta range. Chewing and sucking can produce similar artifacts.

Name: Rocking-patting-artifact
Description: Quasi-rhythmical artifacts in recordings from infants caused by rocking/patting.

Name: Movement-artifact
Description: Example for EEG: Large amplitude artifact, with irregular morphology (usually resembling a slow-wave or a wave with complex morphology) seen in one or several channels, due to movement. If the causing movement is repetitive, the artifact might resemble a rhythmic EEG activity.

Name: Respiration-artifact
Description: Respiration can produce 2 kinds of artifacts. One type is in the form of slow and rhythmic activity, synchronous with the body movements of respiration and mechanically affecting the impedance of (usually) one electrode. The other type can be slow or sharp waves that occur synchronously with inhalation or exhalation and involve those electrodes on which the patient is lying.

Name: Pulse-artifact
Description: Example for EEG: Occurs when an EEG electrode is placed over a pulsating vessel. The pulsation can cause slow waves that may simulate EEG activity. A direct relationship exists between ECG and the pulse waves (200-300 millisecond delay after ECG equals QRS complex).

Name: ECG-artifact
Description: Example for EEG: Far-field potential generated in the heart. The voltage and apparent surface of the artifact vary from derivation to derivation and, consequently, from montage to montage. The artifact is observed best in referential montages using earlobe electrodes A1 and A2. ECG artifact is recognized easily by its rhythmicity/regularity and coincidence with the ECG tracing.

Name: Sweat-artifact
Description: Is a low amplitude undulating waveform that is usually greater than 2 seconds and may appear to be an unstable baseline.

Name: EMG-artifact
Description: Myogenic potentials are the most common artifacts. Frontalis and temporalis muscles (ex..: clenching of jaw muscles) are common causes. Generally, the potentials generated in the muscles are of shorter duration than those generated in the brain. The frequency components are usually beyond 30-50 Hz, and the bursts are arrhythmic.

Name: Non-biological-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Power-supply-artifact
Description: 50-60 Hz artifact. Monomorphic waveform due to 50 or 60 Hz A/C power supply.

Name: Induction-artifact
Description: Artifacts (usually of high frequency) induced by nearby equipment (like in the intensive care unit).

Name: Dialysis-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Artificial-ventilation-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Electrode-pops-artifact
Description: Are brief discharges with a very steep upslope and shallow fall that occur in all leads which include that electrode.

Name: Salt-bridge-artifact
Description: Typically occurs in 1 channel which may appear isoelectric. Only seen in bipolar montage.

Name: Other-artifact
Description: No description available

Name: Finding-property
Description: Descriptive element similar to main HED /Property. Something that pertains to a thing. A characteristic of some entity. A quality or feature regarded as a characteristic or inherent part of someone or something. HED attributes are adjectives or adverbs.

Name: Signal-morphology-property
Description: No description available

Name: Rhythmic-activity-morphology
Description: EEG activity consisting of a sequence of waves approximately constant period.

Name: Delta-activity-morphology
Description: EEG rhythm in the delta (under 4 Hz) range that does not belong to the posterior dominant rhythm (scored under other organized rhythms).

Name: Theta-activity-morphology
Description: EEG rhythm in the theta (4-8 Hz) range that does not belong to the posterior dominant rhythm (scored under other organized rhythm).

Name: Alpha-activity-morphology
Description: EEG rhythm in the alpha range (8-13 Hz) which is considered part of the background (ongoing) activity but does not fulfill the criteria of the posterior dominant rhythm (alpha rhythm).

Name: Beta-activity-morphology
Description: EEG rhythm between 14 and 40 Hz, which is considered part of the background (ongoing) activity but does not fulfill the criteria of the posterior dominant rhythm. Most characteristically: a rhythm from 14 to 40 Hz recorded over the fronto-central regions of the head during wakefulness. Amplitude of the beta rhythm varies but is mostly below 30 microV. Other beta rhythms are most prominent in other locations or are diffuse.

Name: Gamma-activity-morphology
Description: No description available

Name: Spike-morphology
Description: A transient, clearly distinguished from background activity, with pointed peak at a conventional paper speed or time scale and duration from 20 to under 70 ms, i.e. 1/50-1/15 s approximately. Main component is generally negative relative to other areas. Amplitude varies.

Name: Spike-and-slow-wave-morphology
Description: A pattern consisting of a spike followed by a slow wave.

Name: Runs-of-rapid-spikes-morphology
Description: Bursts of spike discharges at a rate from 10 to 25/sec (in most cases somewhat irregular). The bursts last more than 2 seconds (usually 2 to 10 seconds) and it is typically seen in sleep. Synonyms: rhythmic spikes, generalized paroxysmal fast activity, fast paroxysmal rhythms, grand mal discharge, fast beta activity.

Name: Polyspikes-morphology
Description: Two or more consecutive spikes.

Name: Polyspike-and-slow-wave-morphology
Description: Two or more consecutive spikes associated with one or more slow waves.

Name: Sharp-wave-morphology
Description: A transient clearly distinguished from background activity, with pointed peak at a conventional paper speed or time scale, and duration of 70-200 ms, i.e. over 1/4-1/5 s approximately. Main component is generally negative relative to other areas. Amplitude varies.

Name: Sharp-and-slow-wave-morphology
Description: A sequence of a sharp wave and a slow wave.

Name: Slow-sharp-wave-morphology
Description: A transient that bears all the characteristics of a sharp-wave, but exceeds 200 ms. Synonym: blunted sharp wave.

Name: High-frequency-oscillation-morphology
Description: HFO.

Name: Hypsarrhythmia-classic-morphology
Description: Abnormal interictal high amplitude waves and a background of irregular spikes.

Name: Hypsarrhythmia-modified-morphology
Description: No description available

Name: Fast-spike-activity-morphology
Description: A burst consisting of a sequence of spikes. Duration greater than 1 s. Frequency at least in the alpha range.

Name: Low-voltage-fast-activity-morphology
Description: Refers to the fast, and often recruiting activity which can be recorded at the onset of an ictal discharge, particularly in invasive EEG recording of a seizure.

Name: Polysharp-waves-morphology
Description: A sequence of two or more sharp-waves.

Name: Slow-wave-large-amplitude-morphology
Description: No description available

Name: Irregular-delta-or-theta-activity-morphology
Description: EEG activity consisting of repetitive waves of inconsistent wave-duration but in delta and/or theta rang (greater than 125 ms).

Name: Electrodecremental-change-morphology
Description: Sudden desynchronization of electrical activity.

Name: DC-shift-morphology
Description: Shift of negative polarity of the direct current recordings, during seizures.

Name: Disappearance-of-ongoing-activity-morphology
Description: Disappearance of the EEG activity that preceded the ictal event but still remnants of background activity (thus not enough to name it electrodecremental change).

Name: Polymorphic-delta-activity-morphology
Description: EEG activity consisting of waves in the delta range (over 250 ms duration for each wave) but of different morphology.

Name: Frontal-intermittent-rhythmic-delta-activity-morphology
Description: Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA). Fairly regular or approximately sinusoidal waves, mostly occurring in bursts at 1.5-2.5 Hz over the frontal areas of one or both sides of the head. Comment: most commonly associated with unspecified encephalopathy, in adults.

Name: Occipital-intermittent-rhythmic-delta-activity-morphology
Description: Occipital intermittent rhythmic delta activity (OIRDA). Fairly regular or approximately sinusoidal waves, mostly occurring in bursts at 2-3 Hz over the occipital or posterior head regions of one or both sides of the head. Frequently blocked or attenuated by opening the eyes. Comment: most commonly associated with unspecified encephalopathy, in children.

Name: Temporal-intermittent-rhythmic-delta-activity-morphology
Description: Temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (TIRDA). Fairly regular or approximately sinusoidal waves, mostly occurring in bursts at over the temporal areas of one side of the head. Comment: most commonly associated with temporal lobe epilepsy.

Name: Periodic-discharges-morphology
Description: Periodic discharges not further specified (PDs).

Name: Seizure-semiology-manifestation
Description: Semiology is described according to the ILAE Glossary of Descriptive Terminology for Ictal Semiology (Blume et al., 2001). Besides the name, the semiologic finding can also be characterized by the somatotopic modifier, laterality, body part and centricity. Uses Location-property tags.

Name: Semiology-motor-manifestation
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-elementary-motor
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-tonic
Description: A sustained increase in muscle contraction lasting a few seconds to minutes.

Name: Semiology-motor-dystonic
Description: Sustained contractions of both agonist and antagonist muscles producing athetoid or twisting movements, which, when prolonged, may produce abnormal postures.

Name: Semiology-motor-epileptic-spasm
Description: A sudden flexion, extension, or mixed extension flexion of predominantly proximal and truncal muscles that is usually more sustained than a myoclonic movement but not so sustained as a tonic seizure (i.e., about 1 s). Limited forms may occur: grimacing, head nodding. Frequent occurrence in clusters.

Name: Semiology-motor-postural
Description: Adoption of a posture that may be bilaterally symmetric or asymmetric (as in a fencing posture).

Name: Semiology-motor-versive
Description: A sustained, forced conjugate ocular, cephalic, and/or truncal rotation or lateral deviation from the midline.

Name: Semiology-motor-clonic
Description: Myoclonus that is regularly repetitive, involves the same muscle groups, at a frequency of about 2 to 3 c/s, and is prolonged. Synonym: rhythmic myoclonus .

Name: Semiology-motor-myoclonic
Description: Characterized by myoclonus. MYOCLONUS : sudden, brief (lower than 100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction(s) of muscles(s) or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal).

Name: Semiology-motor-jacksonian-march
Description: Term indicating spread of clonic movements through contiguous body parts unilaterally.

Name: Semiology-motor-negative-myoclonus
Description: Characterized by negative myoclonus. NEGATIVE MYOCLONUS: interruption of tonic muscular activity for lower than 500 ms without evidence of preceding myoclonia.

Name: Semiology-motor-tonic-clonic
Description: A sequence consisting of a tonic followed by a clonic phase. Variants such as clonic-tonic-clonic may be seen. Asymmetry of limb posture during the tonic phase of a GTC: one arm is rigidly extended at the elbow (often with the fist clenched tightly and flexed at the wrist), whereas the opposite arm is flexed at the elbow.

Name: Semiology-motor-tonic-clonic-without-figure-of-four
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-tonic-clonic-with-figure-of-four-extension-left-elbow
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-tonic-clonic-with-figure-of-four-extension-right-elbow
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-astatic
Description: Loss of erect posture that results from an atonic, myoclonic, or tonic mechanism. Synonym: drop attack.

Name: Semiology-motor-atonic
Description: Sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone without apparent preceding myoclonic or tonic event lasting greater or equal to 1 to 2 s, involving head, trunk, jaw, or limb musculature.

Name: Semiology-motor-eye-blinking
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-other-elementary-motor
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-mimetic
Description: Facial expression suggesting an emotional state, often fear.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-oroalimentary
Description: Lip smacking, lip pursing, chewing, licking, tooth grinding, or swallowing.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-dacrystic
Description: Bursts of crying.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-dyspraxic
Description: Inability to perform learned movements spontaneously or on command or imitation despite intact relevant motor and sensory systems and adequate comprehension and cooperation.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-manual
Description: 1. Indicates principally distal components, bilateral or unilateral. 2. Fumbling, tapping, manipulating movements.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-gestural
Description: Semipurposive, asynchronous hand movements. Often unilateral.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-pedal
Description: 1. Indicates principally distal components, bilateral or unilateral. 2. Fumbling, tapping, manipulating movements.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-hypermotor
Description: 1. Involves predominantly proximal limb or axial muscles producing irregular sequential ballistic movements, such as pedaling, pelvic thrusting, thrashing, rocking movements. 2. Increase in rate of ongoing movements or inappropriately rapid performance of a movement.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-hypokinetic
Description: A decrease in amplitude and/or rate or arrest of ongoing motor activity.

Name: Semiology-motor-automatisms-gelastic
Description: Bursts of laughter or giggling, usually without an appropriate affective tone.

Name: Semiology-motor-other-automatisms
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-motor-behavioral-arrest
Description: Interruption of ongoing motor activity or of ongoing behaviors with fixed gaze, without movement of the head or trunk (oro-alimentary and hand automatisms may continue).

Name: Semiology-non-motor-manifestation
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-sensory
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-sensory-headache
Description: Headache occurring in close temporal proximity to the seizure or as the sole seizure manifestation.

Name: Semiology-sensory-visual
Description: Flashing or flickering lights, spots, simple patterns, scotomata, or amaurosis.

Name: Semiology-sensory-auditory
Description: Buzzing, drumming sounds or single tones.

Name: Semiology-sensory-olfactory
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-sensory-gustatory
Description: Taste sensations including acidic, bitter, salty, sweet, or metallic.

Name: Semiology-sensory-epigastric
Description: Abdominal discomfort including nausea, emptiness, tightness, churning, butterflies, malaise, pain, and hunger; sensation may rise to chest or throat. Some phenomena may reflect ictal autonomic dysfunction.

Name: Semiology-sensory-somatosensory
Description: Tingling, numbness, electric-shock sensation, sense of movement or desire to move.

Name: Semiology-sensory-painful
Description: Peripheral (lateralized/bilateral), cephalic, abdominal.

Name: Semiology-sensory-autonomic-sensation
Description: A sensation consistent with involvement of the autonomic nervous system, including cardiovascular, gastrointestinal,  sudomotor, vasomotor, and thermoregulatory functions. (Thus autonomic aura; cf. autonomic events  3.0).

Name: Semiology-sensory-other
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-experiential
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-experiential-affective-emotional
Description: Components include fear, depression, joy, and (rarely) anger.

Name: Semiology-experiential-hallucinatory
Description: Composite perceptions without corresponding external stimuli involving visual, auditory, somatosensory, olfactory, and/or gustatory phenomena. Example: hearing  and seeing  people talking.

Name: Semiology-experiential-illusory
Description: An alteration of actual percepts involving the visual, auditory, somatosensory, olfactory, or gustatory systems.

Name: Semiology-experiential-mnemonic
Description: Components that reflect ictal dysmnesia such as feelings of familiarity (deja-vu) and unfamiliarity (jamais-vu).

Name: Semiology-experiential-mnemonic-Deja-vu
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-experiential-mnemonic-Jamais-vu
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-experiential-other
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-dyscognitive
Description: The term describes events in which (1) disturbance of cognition is the predominant or most apparent feature, and (2a) two or more of the following components are involved, or (2b) involvement of such components remains undetermined. Otherwise, use the more specific term (e.g., mnemonic experiential seizure  or hallucinatory experiential seizure). Components of cognition: ++ perception: symbolic conception of sensory information ++ attention: appropriate selection of a principal perception or task ++ emotion: appropriate affective significance of a perception ++ memory: ability to store and retrieve percepts or concepts ++ executive function: anticipation, selection, monitoring of consequences, and initiation of motor activity including praxis, speech.

Name: Semiology-language-related
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-language-related-vocalization
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-language-related-verbalization
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-language-related-dysphasia
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-language-related-aphasia
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-language-related-other
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-autonomic
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-autonomic-pupillary
Description: Mydriasis, miosis (either bilateral or unilateral).

Name: Semiology-autonomic-hypersalivation
Description: Increase in production of saliva leading to uncontrollable drooling

Name: Semiology-autonomic-respiratory-apnoeic
Description: subjective shortness of breath, hyperventilation, stridor, coughing, choking, apnea, oxygen desaturation, neurogenic pulmonary edema.

Name: Semiology-autonomic-cardiovascular
Description: Modifications of heart rate (tachycardia, bradycardia), cardiac arrhythmias (such as sinus arrhythmia, sinus arrest, supraventricular tachycardia, atrial premature depolarizations, ventricular premature depolarizations, atrio-ventricular block, bundle branch block, atrioventricular nodal escape rhythm, asystole).

Name: Semiology-autonomic-gastrointestinal
Description: Nausea, eructation, vomiting, retching, abdominal sensations, abdominal pain, flatulence, spitting, diarrhea.

Name: Semiology-autonomic-urinary-incontinence
Description: urinary urge (intense urinary urge at the beginning of seizures), urinary incontinence, ictal urination (rare symptom of partial seizures without loss of consciousness).

Name: Semiology-autonomic-genital
Description: Sexual auras (erotic thoughts and feelings, sexual arousal and orgasm). Genital auras (unpleasant, sometimes painful, frightening or emotionally neutral somatosensory sensations in the genitals that can be accompanied by ictal orgasm). Sexual automatisms (hypermotor movements consisting of writhing, thrusting, rhythmic movements of the pelvis, arms and legs, sometimes associated with picking and rhythmic manipulation of the groin or genitalia, exhibitionism and masturbation).

Name: Semiology-autonomic-vasomotor
Description: Flushing or pallor (may be accompanied by feelings of warmth, cold and pain).

Name: Semiology-autonomic-sudomotor
Description: Sweating and piloerection (may be accompanied by feelings of warmth, cold and pain).

Name: Semiology-autonomic-thermoregulatory
Description: Hyperthermia, fever.

Name: Semiology-autonomic-other
Description: No description available

Name: Semiology-manifestation-other
Description: No description available

Name: Postictal-semiology-manifestation
Description: No description available

Name: Postictal-semiology-unconscious
Description: No description available

Name: Postictal-semiology-quick-recovery-of-consciousness
Description: Quick recovery of awareness and responsiveness.

Name: Postictal-semiology-aphasia-or-dysphasia
Description: Impaired communication involving language without dysfunction of relevant primary motor or sensory pathways, manifested as impaired comprehension, anomia, parahasic errors or a combination of these.

Name: Postictal-semiology-behavioral-change
Description: Occurring immediately after a aseizure. Including psychosis, hypomanina, obsessive-compulsive behavior.

Name: Postictal-semiology-hemianopia
Description: Postictal visual loss in a a hemi field.

Name: Postictal-semiology-impaired-cognition
Description: Decreased Cognitive performance involving one or more of perception, attention, emotion, memory, execution, praxis, speech.

Name: Postictal-semiology-dysphoria
Description: Depression, irritability, euphoric mood, fear, anxiety.

Name: Postictal-semiology-headache
Description: Headache with features of tension-type or migraine headache that develops within 3 h following the seizure and resolves within 72 h after seizure.

Name: Postictal-semiology-nose-wiping
Description: Noes-wiping usually within 60 sec of seizure offset, usually with the hand ipsilateral to the seizure onset.

Name: Postictal-semiology-anterograde-amnesia
Description: Impaired ability to remember new material.

Name: Postictal-semiology-retrograde-amnesia
Description: Impaired ability to recall previously remember material.

Name: Postictal-semiology-paresis
Description: Todds palsy. Any unilateral postictal dysfunction relating to motor, language, sensory and/or integrative functions.

Name: Postictal-semiology-sleep
Description: Invincible need to sleep after a seizure.

Name: Postictal-semiology-unilateral-myoclonic-jerks
Description: unilateral motor phenomena, other then  specified, occurring in postictal phase.

Name: Postictal-semiology-other-unilateral-motor-phenomena
